            <p rend="align(center)">C O P Y</p>
            <p>Mr. Editor</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">In your <date>April</date> Number there appears a Communication from
                    <placeName>California</placeName><lb/> over the signature of “<hi
                    rend="underline"><persName>Theophilus</persName></hi>” relating to affairs in
                that distant part<lb/> of the Union, which from his statements appear to be
                everything but what<lb/> they should be. Among other things he avers that
                    “<persName>Dr. Henry</persName> then refused to<lb/> make more proselytes” and
                then continues and says: “Two    applied to the<lb/> Congregation Shearith Israel to
                be married to widows having no children,<lb/> which <persName>Dr. Henry</persName>
                refused to do, as he stated that the widows must have<lb/> and after continuing his
                bill of complaints in the same style, finishes by evoking<lb/> your attention “to
                the right minded Israelites of <placeName>California</placeName>” which you in
                a<lb/> very kind and philosophic manner proceed so to do, much no doubt to your
                own<lb/> satisfaction, but perhaps without strict regard to the law which the
                question<lb/> raised. Where do you find any such law as “The marriage of the
                two<lb/> certainly not in the Eben Haezer, the place quoted by you in your <hi
                    rend="underline">Note</hi>,”<lb/> and Sir could you find it in any other place;
                perhaps not. And not content with<lb/> simply answering the question propounded, you
                say “it would be the same if simple<lb/> Israelites.” Now no such law as that can be
                found in any book of Standard<lb/> Authority among any Machtoh authors in the known
                world, and why and for what<lb/> purpose do you answer “the right minded” people in
                that manner, when you know, if<lb/> you know anything about the matter at all, that
                in the way the case was stated,<lb/> there could be no objection to the marriage of
                the widows to the two or<lb/> to any other Israelites.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">“That a <persName>Cohen</persName> is prohibited form marrying a <hi
                    rend="underline">Chabuzah</hi>” is stated by you,<lb/> with reference to Iben
                Heazer V.1 is a most singular thing, for the word<lb/>
                <hi rend="underline">Chabuzah</hi> is not mentioned in that place and as to the
                word, perhaps you would<lb/> have done much better in your “Note” if you had told
                the “right minded” correctly<lb/> where it is to be found or what is the meaning of
                the word; but Mr. Editor things<lb/> both in <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName> and
                    <placeName>California</placeName> appear to be much out of place; in one
                place<lb/> a <hi rend="underline">Dr</hi>. refused “to make any <hi rend="underline"
                    >more</hi> proselytes” while in the other an Editor refers<lb/> to places and
                laws not to be found, and writes about a “Chabuzah” which puts all<lb/> his numerous
                readers on tiptoe of expectation hoping that in his next Number he<lb/> will tell
                them where the law is to be found which forbade a childless widow from<lb/> being
                married without and the meaning of the word chabuzah.</p>
            <p rend="indent(9)">
                <persName role="author">S. A.</persName>
            </p>
            <p>Private</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Can you insert the above in <date>May</date> No.</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">
                <persName role="author">Simon Ahaland, M. D.</persName>
            </p>
